04598nam a22007095i 9781487549183DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232024onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875491837 a10.3138/97814875491832doi  a(DE-B1597)672117  a(OCoLC)1409701867  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aDK5095.G47bS73 2024 7aHIS0670002bisacsh04a947.7/32231 aStaples, John R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJohann Cornies, the Mennonites, and Russian Colonialism in Southern Ukraine /cJohn R. Staples. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2023] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b2 b&w illustrations, 2 b&w maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTsarist and Soviet Mennonite Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations and Maps -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Land of Opportunity, 1804–1817 -- t3 A Public Life, 1818–1824 -- t4 Awakening, 1824–1828 -- t5 Imposing Order, 1828–1834 -- t6 Mennonites and the Era of Small Reforms, 1834–1838 -- t7 “A Useful Man,” 1838–1842 -- t8 The Warkentin Affair, 1841–1842 -- t9 An Agent of the State, 1842–1847 -- t10 Conclusion: “Something for the Future,” 1847–1848 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late eighteenth century, the Russian Empire opened the grasslands of southern Ukraine to agricultural settlement by new colonists, among them Prussian Mennonites. Mennonite colonization was one aspect of the empire’s consolidation and modernization of its multi-ethnic territory. In the colony of Molochnaia, the dominant personality of the early nineteenth century was Johann Cornies (1789–1848), a hard-driving modernizer and intimate of senior Russian officials whose papers provide unique access into events in Ukraine in this era. Johann Cornies, the Mennonites, and Russian Colonialism in Southern Ukraine uses the life story of Johann Cornies to explore how colonial subjects interacted with Russian imperial policy. The book reveals how tsarist imperial policy shifted toward Russification in the 1830s and 1840s and became increasingly intolerant of ethno-cultural and ethno-religious minorities. It shows that Russia employed the Mennonite settlement as a colonial laboratory of modernity, and that the Mennonites were among Russia’s most economically productive subjects. This microhistory illuminates the role of Johann Cornies as a mediator between the empire and the Mennonite colonists, and it ultimately aims to bring light to the history of nineteenth-century Russia and Ukraine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgricultural colonieszUkraine, SouthernxHistoryy19th century. 0aGermanszUkraine, SouthernxHistoryy19th century. 0aMennoniteszUkraine, SouthernxHistoryy19th century. 0aRussificationzUkraine, SouthernxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ukraine.2bisacsh  aJohann Cornies.  aMennonite settlement.  aMennonites.  aMolochnaia.  aRussian colonialism.  aRussian imperialism.  aUkrainian steppe.  aWarkentin Affair.  amicrohistory.  amodernization.  apietism.  asouthern Ukraine.  awheat.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079737440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754918340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487549183423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487549183/original  a978-3-11-079737-4  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles